00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:16.030
So as Richard said, I
covered policy and politics

00:05:16.030 --> 00:05:17.860
at "The Post" for five years.

00:05:17.860 --> 00:05:20.180
Before that, I was at
"The American Prospect."

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:24.610
And the focus of my work
has always been policy,

00:05:24.610 --> 00:05:27.600
particularly health care
policy, economic policy

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:31.540
from roughly 2008 to 2012, the
complete and utter collapse

00:05:31.540 --> 00:05:33.020
of the global financial system.

00:05:33.020 --> 00:05:36.210
It's been a good ride of things
going terribly for the world.

00:05:36.210 --> 00:05:40.980
And that has been, on the
one hand a lot of fun,

00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:43.220
because I came into all
this through a back door.

00:05:43.220 --> 00:05:44.870
I didn't want to
be a journalist.

00:05:44.870 --> 00:05:46.745
I had never thought
about being a journalist.

00:05:46.745 --> 00:05:49.000
I started a blog
and things kind of

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.820
took on some momentum from
there when I was in college.

00:05:52.820 --> 00:05:55.440
But what I learned in
blogging was that actually you

00:05:55.440 --> 00:06:00.770
had this incredible ability
to develop audiences and dig

00:06:00.770 --> 00:06:03.430
into topics that
simply didn't work that

00:06:03.430 --> 00:06:05.630
well in traditional
news formats.

00:06:05.630 --> 00:06:08.060
When you're covering
something like Obamacare,

00:06:08.060 --> 00:06:12.560
the sort of really thorny,
big, complex systems.

00:06:12.560 --> 00:06:15.320
Writing about it once
isn't good enough.

00:06:15.320 --> 00:06:16.960
I came up through magazines.

00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:18.589
I went to "The
American Prospect."

00:06:18.589 --> 00:06:20.380
And I interned at "The
Washington Monthly."

00:06:20.380 --> 00:06:23.111
I remember we'd always be
in these editorial meetings,

00:06:23.111 --> 00:06:25.110
and you would always have
to convince the editor

00:06:25.110 --> 00:06:27.080
that whatever you were
going to say was new.

00:06:27.080 --> 00:06:29.509
And so we'd say,
well, I got this idea.

00:06:29.509 --> 00:06:30.550
I think it's a good idea.

00:06:30.550 --> 00:06:31.240
And everybody would agree.

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:33.448
And then they'd be like,
yeah, but "The New Republic"

00:06:33.448 --> 00:06:35.750
did that in June of 2004.

00:06:35.750 --> 00:06:37.847
And it's like, so?

00:06:37.847 --> 00:06:39.930
Nobody read "The New
Republic" doing that in 2004,

00:06:39.930 --> 00:06:43.950
and if they did, they
don't remember it.

00:06:43.950 --> 00:06:48.180
I've probably written 7,000
articles on Obamacare.

00:06:48.180 --> 00:06:51.110
And what frustrated me
about that experience

00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:52.865
was that I was
building something

00:06:52.865 --> 00:06:54.740
that I thought had value
to the reader, which

00:06:54.740 --> 00:06:56.420
was a body of knowledge
about Obamacare.

00:06:56.420 --> 00:06:58.630
I actually have
read the dam Bill.

00:06:58.630 --> 00:07:02.840
And I don't recommend
it, by the way.

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:05.650
If you want to do
something, I recommended

00:07:05.650 --> 00:07:09.060
doing something other than
reading the Obamacare bill.

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:12.860
But I would get every
day these emails

00:07:12.860 --> 00:07:16.050
from readers who, what
they needed to know

00:07:16.050 --> 00:07:17.994
were the basics of
what was going on,

00:07:17.994 --> 00:07:20.160
what were the exchanges,
how did the subsidies work,

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:22.120
how did the mandate work.

00:07:22.120 --> 00:07:27.050
But the news does
not prize the basics.

00:07:27.050 --> 00:07:30.140
The basics get locked in
actually pretty early.

00:07:30.140 --> 00:07:32.550
The news prize are parts of
it that will change, And then

00:07:32.550 --> 00:07:35.050
the parts of it that are
in conflict every day.

00:07:35.050 --> 00:07:37.529
And so those are the parts
within the news pegs,

00:07:37.529 --> 00:07:39.070
the things that your
editors actually

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:40.780
want from you, the
things that feel new.

00:07:40.780 --> 00:07:43.550
You can actually say, well,
look, a politician said x.

00:07:43.550 --> 00:07:45.560
I'm writing a thing about x.

00:07:45.560 --> 00:07:48.110
They're not the thing that
the reader needs the most.

00:07:48.110 --> 00:07:50.900
So one thing I recognized
while doing this coverage

00:07:50.900 --> 00:07:53.990
was that as much as myself,
and then later Sarah Cliffe,

00:07:53.990 --> 00:07:56.020
who's by far I think
the best health care

00:07:56.020 --> 00:07:58.515
reporter in the
country, were really

00:07:58.515 --> 00:08:00.640
I think doing a pretty good
job covering Obamacare,

00:08:00.640 --> 00:08:02.100
certainly trying to.

00:08:02.100 --> 00:08:04.810
We were not building the
thing our readers needed.

00:08:04.810 --> 00:08:08.010
We were building an incredibly
fractured knowledge base

00:08:08.010 --> 00:08:09.920
that you couldn't
get to unless you

00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:12.710
had just incredible Google-fu.

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:16.650
This is what got me thinking a
lot about whether we were doing

00:08:16.650 --> 00:08:18.880
the news right in
the digital age.

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:20.750
And the more I
gave this thought,

00:08:20.750 --> 00:08:24.280
I sort of came to think there
were three, and arguably four,

00:08:24.280 --> 00:08:26.230
but for me, three
relevant differences

00:08:26.230 --> 00:08:28.850
between doing print
journalism, which

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:31.846
structured even digital
journals to a greater degree

00:08:31.846 --> 00:08:33.429
than I think people
realize, and doing

00:08:33.429 --> 00:08:35.330
purely digital journalism.

00:08:35.330 --> 00:08:37.169
The first difference is speed.

00:08:37.169 --> 00:08:40.251
And we as an industry
figured out how to do that.

00:08:40.251 --> 00:08:42.000
We probably figured
that one out too well.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.820
I think if anything, we're
a little bit too fast.

00:08:44.820 --> 00:08:47.310
But we figured out that you
could be much faster online

00:08:47.310 --> 00:08:48.720
than you ever could be in print.

00:08:48.720 --> 00:08:52.490
So speed, you can put
the check in that box.

00:08:52.490 --> 00:08:58.830
The second was length, and
I'd give us a C- on length.

00:08:58.830 --> 00:09:00.552
An economist will
always tell you

00:09:00.552 --> 00:09:02.580
in any industry,
what you want to look

00:09:02.580 --> 00:09:04.244
for is the relevant scarcity.

00:09:04.244 --> 00:09:06.535
You want to look for the
thing people don't have enough

00:09:06.535 --> 00:09:09.060
of because that is going
to drive what they do.

00:09:09.060 --> 00:09:11.300
In journalism, the
fundamental scarcity

00:09:11.300 --> 00:09:13.035
has always been the
number of pages.

00:09:13.035 --> 00:09:16.870
You have 64 in a magazine, you
have whatever number you had,

00:09:16.870 --> 00:09:19.510
given the advertising you
had in that day's newspaper.

00:09:19.510 --> 00:09:23.240
And everything was shaped
by this incredibly ruthless

00:09:23.240 --> 00:09:26.430
competition for column inches.

00:09:26.430 --> 00:09:28.560
At "The Washington Post,"
at "The New York Times,"

00:09:28.560 --> 00:09:30.601
you don't talk about how
many words with stories,

00:09:30.601 --> 00:09:32.870
you literally talk
about it in inches.

00:09:32.870 --> 00:09:35.525
This was very
confusing to me when

00:09:35.525 --> 00:09:37.150
they would say, how
long is your story?

00:09:37.150 --> 00:09:38.274
And I would say, 800 words.

00:09:38.274 --> 00:09:39.860
And they would say,
how many inches?

00:09:39.860 --> 00:09:42.130
And I would say,
it's the internet.

00:09:42.130 --> 00:09:44.601
It doesn't have inches.

00:09:44.601 --> 00:09:46.100
But that was the
right way to think.

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:47.224
You had to lay out a paper.

00:09:47.224 --> 00:09:48.500
It is about inches.

00:09:48.500 --> 00:09:51.310
So an enormous amount
of how we did our work

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:54.630
was about how do we give people
the absolute most information

00:09:54.630 --> 00:09:56.240
in the least amount of space.

00:09:56.240 --> 00:10:00.270
And we made, as an industry, an
enormous number of decisions,

00:10:00.270 --> 00:10:05.860
and compromises, and concessions
to the tyranny of page length.

00:10:05.860 --> 00:10:08.260
The way we write articles,
reverse pyramid style,

00:10:08.260 --> 00:10:11.640
is a mixture of dealing with
the problems of the telegraph,

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:13.790
because if you
get cut off, well,

00:10:13.790 --> 00:10:16.070
the parts that got cut off
can just be lopped off.

00:10:16.070 --> 00:10:17.890
It doesn't matter.

00:10:17.890 --> 00:10:20.626
And then secondarily,
it is about getting

00:10:20.626 --> 00:10:22.000
the maximum amount
of information

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.920
into the minimum
amount of space.

00:10:24.920 --> 00:10:27.940
You don't have that
problem on the internet.

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:30.510
Do any of y'all read ClickHole?

00:10:30.510 --> 00:10:31.010
Good.

00:10:31.010 --> 00:10:34.230
It's a future of news.

00:10:34.230 --> 00:10:36.805
ClickHole had a piece
recently that said--

00:10:36.805 --> 00:10:38.680
I'm going to maybe mangle
the headline a bit,

00:10:38.680 --> 00:10:41.330
but I went on this whaling
trip and it completely

00:10:41.330 --> 00:10:42.587
changed my life.

00:10:42.587 --> 00:10:45.170
And you clicked it, and it was
the entire text of "Moby Dick."

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:47.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:47.510 --> 00:10:50.270
Which was a great joke,
because you all laughed.

00:10:50.270 --> 00:10:53.640
But it's also a profound
thing to think about.

00:10:53.640 --> 00:10:56.510
They put up the entire
text of "Moby Dick," which

00:10:56.510 --> 00:11:00.277
is even longer than Obamacare
I think on a per word level--

00:11:00.277 --> 00:11:01.610
although I haven't checked that.

00:11:01.610 --> 00:11:05.427
And then they just published
a bunch of other articles.

00:11:05.427 --> 00:11:08.010
A world in which you can put up
the entire text of "Moby Dick"

00:11:08.010 --> 00:11:11.010
and then anything else you want
is a really different world.

00:11:11.010 --> 00:11:13.130
It is a really different world.

00:11:13.130 --> 00:11:15.600
And in journals I think
we're only just beginning

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:20.670
to figure out what being
unleashed from length means.

00:11:20.670 --> 00:11:22.430
I think we are very,
very young at that.

00:11:22.430 --> 00:11:25.810
I mean even in my experience
at all kinds of magazines

00:11:25.810 --> 00:11:27.660
and newspapers,
you'll have people

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:30.100
do these incredible
pieces that we

00:11:30.100 --> 00:11:31.960
get sent all over
the world to do.

00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:34.630
And the piece really
should be 10,000 words.

00:11:34.630 --> 00:11:38.470
But it'll get locked down to
1,600 or 2,300 for the magazine

00:11:38.470 --> 00:11:39.640
or for the paper.

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:41.860
And then we won't-- not
because we think it's better,

00:11:41.860 --> 00:11:43.526
just because that's
what we need to do--

00:11:43.526 --> 00:11:45.880
then we won't put the
real version online.

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:48.740
We somehow bring the
constraint of print online.

00:11:48.740 --> 00:11:52.085
So there are times when we're
getting past that now and times

00:11:52.085 --> 00:11:52.710
when we aren't.

00:11:52.710 --> 00:11:55.397
So I'd give us a
partial pass on that.

00:11:55.397 --> 00:11:56.980
The third thing, and
the thing I think

00:11:56.980 --> 00:11:59.420
people don't think enough
about, is persistence.

00:11:59.420 --> 00:12:02.040
The web is persistent
in a way print is not.

00:12:02.040 --> 00:12:06.030
If you don't ever throw out
your newspapers and magazines,

00:12:06.030 --> 00:12:09.910
they will eventually grow mold
and you will inhale it and die.

00:12:09.910 --> 00:12:15.740
It is very important to
throw out print news.

00:12:15.740 --> 00:12:18.490
That is a really
profound way of thinking,

00:12:18.490 --> 00:12:21.120
that the articles you do
every day or every week

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:22.950
or every month are
going to be trash.

00:12:22.950 --> 00:12:25.010
They're going to be
a first approximation

00:12:25.010 --> 00:12:26.930
inaccessible to readership.

00:12:26.930 --> 00:12:29.700
Fundamentally, the publishing
tools built for the web,

00:12:29.700 --> 00:12:31.240
and the way we do
news on the web

00:12:31.240 --> 00:12:33.970
actually apes that, even though
it really doesn't need to.

00:12:33.970 --> 00:12:37.130
We structure our home
pages by the newest stuff,

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:39.096
the stuff that is
happening right now.

00:12:39.096 --> 00:12:40.720
The other stuff goes
into the archives.

00:12:40.720 --> 00:12:41.860
It's not very findable.

00:12:41.860 --> 00:12:43.030
You can go click and search.

00:12:43.030 --> 00:12:44.530
I mean there are
things you can do.

00:12:44.530 --> 00:12:47.540
And everyone has a search
product for their own website

00:12:47.540 --> 00:12:49.620
that is just wildly
inferior to Google's.

00:12:49.620 --> 00:12:52.050
So there are things you
guys do particularly.

00:12:52.050 --> 00:12:55.020
But in general, those archives
become radically less valuable

00:12:55.020 --> 00:12:57.250
with every passing day.

00:12:57.250 --> 00:12:59.030
The thing that I
am obsessed with,

00:12:59.030 --> 00:13:01.260
and the thing that
Vox is obsessed with

00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:04.090
is persistence,
because that, to me,

00:13:04.090 --> 00:13:07.430
is the answer for the
problem I had with Obamacare.

00:13:07.430 --> 00:13:12.810
Persistence allows me to write
7,000 Obamacare articles.

00:13:12.810 --> 00:13:15.660
Filter the relevant and
changing information.

00:13:18.920 --> 00:13:20.810
Pull the body of knowledge
in those articles

00:13:20.810 --> 00:13:24.480
out into something coherent,
continuously update it.

00:13:24.480 --> 00:13:26.160
And instead of
constantly creating

00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:29.460
new things where we redo the
work, simply update the thing

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:30.740
we have.

00:13:30.740 --> 00:13:34.960
And instead of redoing 90% of
the work or 95% of the work,

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:36.700
change 5% of the work.

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:38.640
And I can give you guys
a slew of examples,

00:13:38.640 --> 00:13:40.556
ranging from with have
these card stacks which

00:13:40.556 --> 00:13:42.790
are kind of the body
of knowledge solution.

00:13:42.790 --> 00:13:45.430
Not that we have figured that
out, but we are working on it.

00:13:45.430 --> 00:13:48.900
And that is where we sort
of take ongoing new stories

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:53.250
and build out a sort of modular,
continuously updated topic

00:13:53.250 --> 00:13:56.040
resource on them that we can
always attach to articles.

00:13:56.040 --> 00:13:58.284
So that anybody coming
into the news midstream,

00:13:58.284 --> 00:13:59.950
you're coming into
Obamacare nine months

00:13:59.950 --> 00:14:01.470
after the discussion
has started.

00:14:01.470 --> 00:14:03.680
You're looking into what's
going on in Syria years

00:14:03.680 --> 00:14:05.202
after the Civil War has begun.

00:14:05.202 --> 00:14:06.660
We have the thing
where we can say,

00:14:06.660 --> 00:14:07.951
here's where you get caught up.

00:14:07.951 --> 00:14:09.485
Here's where we
can give you what

00:14:09.485 --> 00:14:11.860
you need to know to understand
all the other news stories

00:14:11.860 --> 00:14:12.790
we're writing.

00:14:12.790 --> 00:14:14.010
But in other ways, too.

00:14:14.010 --> 00:14:15.070
We did a feature.

00:14:15.070 --> 00:14:17.510
We sent Sarah Cliffe to Vermont
to report on their effort

00:14:17.510 --> 00:14:19.130
to do single payer.

00:14:19.130 --> 00:14:20.970
She did an incredible
feature from Vermont.

00:14:20.970 --> 00:14:23.730
Six months later, Vermont's
single payer collapsed,

00:14:23.730 --> 00:14:25.240
their effort collapsed.

00:14:25.240 --> 00:14:27.470
So she did another feature.

00:14:27.470 --> 00:14:31.430
What that feature did was
it was 40% or 50% new work,

00:14:31.430 --> 00:14:34.910
and then 50% the contextual
parts of her original piece

00:14:34.910 --> 00:14:36.430
that were still relevant.

00:14:36.430 --> 00:14:38.850
That gave us the ability
to be much more efficient.

00:14:38.850 --> 00:14:40.560
What single payer is.

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:43.150
What Vermont had been trying
to do had not changed.

00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:44.990
All that work was relevant.

00:14:44.990 --> 00:14:47.920
A lot of it is just getting
past the discomfort we feel.

00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:52.010
A discomfort that I think is
born of the lessons and habits

00:14:52.010 --> 00:14:54.640
we learned from print with
simply reusing our work

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:55.790
efficiently.

00:14:55.790 --> 00:14:58.110
So for me, what we
need to figure out

00:14:58.110 --> 00:15:01.176
is really speed, which I
think we're pretty far on.

00:15:01.176 --> 00:15:03.800
Length, which I think we've done
some work on this in industry,

00:15:03.800 --> 00:15:04.550
but are not there.

00:15:04.550 --> 00:15:07.900
And persistence, which I
think we are nowhere on.

00:15:07.900 --> 00:15:10.000
And if you were building
a news organization,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:14.350
if the news was invented today
as opposed to in the past,

00:15:14.350 --> 00:15:17.160
I think the way those
three things interacted

00:15:17.160 --> 00:15:19.370
with it would just be
tremendously different.

00:15:19.370 --> 00:15:21.230
And it's going to
take us a while

00:15:21.230 --> 00:15:22.600
to figure out how to do that.

00:15:22.600 --> 00:15:27.130
But for me, what Vox is about,
what measures our success to

00:15:27.130 --> 00:15:31.750
me is not just unique visitors
a month, or page views,

00:15:31.750 --> 00:15:33.761
or any of these sort
of other raw metrics.

00:15:33.761 --> 00:15:35.260
In the long run,
it's whether or not

00:15:35.260 --> 00:15:39.720
we are actually building a sort
of truly digital, genuinely

00:15:39.720 --> 00:15:41.700
more efficient
newsroom that allows

00:15:41.700 --> 00:15:45.070
us to serve our readers
better and do better work more

00:15:45.070 --> 00:15:47.249
efficiently.

00:15:47.249 --> 00:15:49.040
RICHARD GINGRAS: So
let's talk a little bit

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:52.200
further about persistence,
because as you point out,

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:56.260
I think it's an absolutely
crucial dimension to how

00:15:56.260 --> 00:15:58.130
journalists think
about the future.

00:15:58.130 --> 00:16:00.130
And to your point
about inches, it's

00:16:00.130 --> 00:16:03.930
always-- because in the prior
era it was edition-oriented

00:16:03.930 --> 00:16:07.200
and yesterday's stuff went away.

00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:10.244
Yesterday's stuff went into the
archive, went into the morgue.

00:16:10.244 --> 00:16:11.660
I mean that's what
they called it.

00:16:11.660 --> 00:16:14.060
Where content went to die.

00:16:14.060 --> 00:16:16.450
And obviously, in
this realm it doesn't.

00:16:16.450 --> 00:16:21.970
Persistence is a key attribute
of the web in general.

00:16:21.970 --> 00:16:25.510
Wikipedia proves that every day.

00:16:25.510 --> 00:16:27.000
Persistent links have value.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.230
Build value over time.

00:16:29.230 --> 00:16:32.850
You have approached this
with the card stacks.

00:16:32.850 --> 00:16:36.300
So talk a little bit more
about the card stacks.

00:16:36.300 --> 00:16:37.380
How they working?

00:16:37.380 --> 00:16:39.559
How are users
responding to them?

00:16:39.559 --> 00:16:41.100
What do you think
is good about them?

00:16:41.100 --> 00:16:42.516
Where would you
like to take them?

00:16:42.516 --> 00:16:43.350
EZRA KLEIN: Sure.

00:16:43.350 --> 00:16:44.710
Am I allowed to curse at Google?

00:16:44.710 --> 00:16:45.410
RICHARD GINGRAS: Oh, gosh yeah.

00:16:45.410 --> 00:16:46.600
EZRA KLEIN: Oh, good.

00:16:46.600 --> 00:16:47.990
RICHARD GINGRAS: Gosh, darn it.

00:16:47.990 --> 00:16:50.560
EZRA KLEIN: The card
stacks are fucking hard.

00:16:50.560 --> 00:16:53.250
They are, by far, the
hardest thing we do.

00:16:53.250 --> 00:16:57.700
So for those of you who don't
have Vox shirts, the card

00:16:57.700 --> 00:17:01.590
stacks are we built this
metaphor around the index cards

00:17:01.590 --> 00:17:04.780
that some of us
used in high school.

00:17:04.780 --> 00:17:06.250
Sort of the initial
idea of Vox was

00:17:06.250 --> 00:17:09.000
could we create this giant--
these topic guides continuously

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.180
updated that would appear
under every article.

00:17:11.180 --> 00:17:13.660
Somebody correctly noted
that would be very long.

00:17:13.660 --> 00:17:16.099
So the brilliant
UX designers at Vox

00:17:16.099 --> 00:17:19.829
came up with this cards
concept where-- so Obamacare,

00:17:19.829 --> 00:17:21.200
for instance, is a card stack.

00:17:21.200 --> 00:17:22.980
I think it's roughly 30 cards.

00:17:22.980 --> 00:17:24.730
The first one would
be what is Obamacare?

00:17:24.730 --> 00:17:27.140
Another one will be what is
a health insurance exchange?

00:17:27.140 --> 00:17:29.610
Another one will be how to
see individual mandate work?

00:17:29.610 --> 00:17:31.465
Another one will be
is Obamacare popular?

00:17:31.465 --> 00:17:35.410
A third will be-- we're
not at third of that point.

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:40.380
Anyway, point is, that
they are very detailed.

00:17:40.380 --> 00:17:43.225
The idea is that we do
our daily news reporting

00:17:43.225 --> 00:17:44.850
and we filter that
reporting into them.

00:17:44.850 --> 00:17:47.100
The cards themselves
can be pulled apart.

00:17:47.100 --> 00:17:50.050
We can attach any
individual one to a story.

00:17:50.050 --> 00:17:53.622
They take a tremendous amount
of work to do at the front end.

00:17:53.622 --> 00:17:55.830
If we'd been doing this for
years it would be easier.

00:17:55.830 --> 00:17:59.260
It would be more of a flywheel,
to use the metaphor that

00:17:59.260 --> 00:18:00.910
seems so dominant out here.

00:18:00.910 --> 00:18:04.570
But to just start one
up from the beginning

00:18:04.570 --> 00:18:06.240
is just a lot of work.

00:18:06.240 --> 00:18:11.390
We have roughly 120
of them now, roughly.

00:18:11.390 --> 00:18:13.769
We have learned
a lot of lessons.

00:18:13.769 --> 00:18:15.060
I'll walk through some of them.

00:18:15.060 --> 00:18:18.812
We are actually doing
a big editorial sort

00:18:18.812 --> 00:18:21.020
of V2 on card stacks right
now that we're rolling out

00:18:21.020 --> 00:18:23.370
internally in the
next week or so.

00:18:23.370 --> 00:18:25.160
And we're in the midst
of a huge product

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:26.400
redesign on card stacks.

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:30.830
I mean card stacks are something
we really hacked together.

00:18:30.830 --> 00:18:32.960
And so I think they're
going to improve rapidly.

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:34.210
But we've been learning a lot.

00:18:34.210 --> 00:18:36.335
We had didn't know how to
do this before we did it.

00:18:36.335 --> 00:18:38.420
And one of the reasons
it's been so hard

00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:41.129
is that there aren't actually
examples for us to follow.

00:18:41.129 --> 00:18:42.920
Everything else, there's
so much great work

00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:44.660
being done on the
web by so many people

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:48.990
that you can do really rapid
best practices discovery.

00:18:48.990 --> 00:18:50.810
On card stacks, not at all.

00:18:50.810 --> 00:18:53.720
So the initial
theory of card stacks

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:55.930
conceived of them as
a reference material.

00:18:55.930 --> 00:18:57.360
I think we really
thought of them

00:18:57.360 --> 00:18:59.980
in terms of the article format.

00:18:59.980 --> 00:19:01.750
So you would have an
article, and articles

00:19:01.750 --> 00:19:03.792
almost by necessity have
a lot of jargon in them.

00:19:03.792 --> 00:19:05.958
I'm going to keep using
Obamacare here as an example

00:19:05.958 --> 00:19:07.210
here, if people don't mind.

00:19:07.210 --> 00:19:09.220
You have to talk about
insurance exchanges,

00:19:09.220 --> 00:19:13.620
the individual mandate,
subsidies, the medical loss

00:19:13.620 --> 00:19:14.580
ratio.

00:19:14.580 --> 00:19:16.871
These are things that you
actually don't-- there is not

00:19:16.871 --> 00:19:19.260
a more precise term
out there for them.

00:19:19.260 --> 00:19:20.940
Those are just the terms.

00:19:20.940 --> 00:19:25.740
So what we imagined
was these cards

00:19:25.740 --> 00:19:28.290
that would actually have
really detailed explanations

00:19:28.290 --> 00:19:30.980
of the core concepts
in a news story.

00:19:30.980 --> 00:19:34.480
So we designed a discovery
mechanism for them

00:19:34.480 --> 00:19:36.080
that was really
based on the article.

00:19:36.080 --> 00:19:37.579
So you have this
yellow highlighting

00:19:37.579 --> 00:19:39.700
in articles that
signifies a card is here.

00:19:39.700 --> 00:19:42.110
We can attach the
card into the article.

00:19:42.110 --> 00:19:43.640
And we write them,
and initially we

00:19:43.640 --> 00:19:45.680
wrote them as
reference materials.

00:19:45.680 --> 00:19:48.780
So we kind of thought about
what is each piece of the story

00:19:48.780 --> 00:19:52.570
that we might need to
refer back to a lot.

00:19:52.570 --> 00:19:54.750
As we watched the user
behavior on the cards,

00:19:54.750 --> 00:19:56.370
that is not how people use them.

00:19:56.370 --> 00:19:58.360
They did go from the
articles occassionally--

00:19:58.360 --> 00:19:59.950
I mean it's not that
it didn't happen.

00:19:59.950 --> 00:20:01.830
But the really big
wins in card stacks,

00:20:01.830 --> 00:20:03.621
and what we really
found that surprised us,

00:20:03.621 --> 00:20:06.300
when people went into a card,
they read about eight cards.

00:20:06.300 --> 00:20:08.500
That is a tremendous
number on the internet.

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:12.061
Our bounce rate was in
the single digits, which

00:20:12.061 --> 00:20:13.560
for every news story
I've ever seen,

00:20:13.560 --> 00:20:18.260
it's usually
between 70% to 100%.

00:20:18.260 --> 00:20:21.290
So people were going in and
they were going in deep.

00:20:21.290 --> 00:20:23.700
And the way people were
finding them primarily,

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:25.534
for the ones that
really worked, was

00:20:25.534 --> 00:20:26.950
that they were
searching them out.

00:20:26.950 --> 00:20:30.670
It was not somebody coming and
reading an article and saying,

00:20:30.670 --> 00:20:32.350
oh, I don't
understand that word.

00:20:32.350 --> 00:20:33.850
It was somebody
coming and saying,

00:20:33.850 --> 00:20:35.610
I don't understand Obamacare.

00:20:35.610 --> 00:20:37.760
I don't understand the
Israel-Palestine conflict.

00:20:37.760 --> 00:20:39.425
I don't understand bitcoin.

00:20:39.425 --> 00:20:41.250
The answer is nobody
understands bitcoin.

00:20:43.790 --> 00:20:45.890
So this forced a real overhaul.

00:20:45.890 --> 00:20:48.670
We had not even designed
discovery mechanisms

00:20:48.670 --> 00:20:52.189
that were consonant to that.

00:20:52.189 --> 00:20:54.230
There is actually not a
home for the card stacks.

00:20:54.230 --> 00:20:55.540
We build a home for
the cards stacks,

00:20:55.540 --> 00:20:57.330
we build a search
for the card stacks.

00:20:57.330 --> 00:20:59.680
But the real challenge was
how we were writing them.

00:20:59.680 --> 00:21:01.680
We were writing them as
reference materials that

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:04.610
were meant to be, in many ways,
broken up and disaggregated.

00:21:04.610 --> 00:21:06.380
We've moved much more
towards writing them

00:21:06.380 --> 00:21:08.040
as full topic guides
that are meant

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:10.550
to be consumed by
somebody really

00:21:10.550 --> 00:21:14.010
sort of trying to dig deep.

00:21:14.010 --> 00:21:15.930
So we're doing a lot
of editorial revision

00:21:15.930 --> 00:21:17.830
on what are the best
ways to do a card stack

00:21:17.830 --> 00:21:19.780
and how to think about
the writing of it.

00:21:19.780 --> 00:21:22.130
But it is much more-- we
almost look at it much more

00:21:22.130 --> 00:21:24.290
like writing a feature
now than we think of it

00:21:24.290 --> 00:21:27.840
like writing Wikipedia
or an encyclopedia entry.

00:21:27.840 --> 00:21:30.810
And there's going to be a lot
of product changes in the coming

00:21:30.810 --> 00:21:36.195
months that will be aligned to
that, which, unfortunately, I

00:21:36.195 --> 00:21:37.320
can't talk about yet.

00:21:37.320 --> 00:21:41.070
But we are sort of
overall, I would

00:21:41.070 --> 00:21:43.610
say that we've actually
moved very dramatically.

00:21:43.610 --> 00:21:45.957
Now, you also asked how
are they performing.

00:21:45.957 --> 00:21:47.790
The answer is there's
incredible variability

00:21:47.790 --> 00:21:48.914
in how are they performing.

00:21:48.914 --> 00:21:51.155
A lot of it has to
do with you people.

00:21:51.155 --> 00:21:52.696
They perform really
well when they're

00:21:52.696 --> 00:21:55.290
at the top of the
Google results.

00:21:55.290 --> 00:21:58.730
So we had a card stack
on ISIS, which is just

00:21:58.730 --> 00:22:02.110
an exceptional piece of work by
a writer named Zack Beauchamp.

00:22:02.110 --> 00:22:05.520
And that card stack on
ISIS was very, very early

00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:09.472
in the conflict with ISIS
very early and their rise.

00:22:09.472 --> 00:22:11.430
The structure is one of
our sort of normal ones

00:22:11.430 --> 00:22:13.270
which we call Xfacts.

00:22:13.270 --> 00:22:16.425
I think it's at this point,
17 facts about ISIS and Iraq

00:22:16.425 --> 00:22:18.050
you should know.

00:22:18.050 --> 00:22:21.500
Each card, it begins with ISIS
used to be al-Qaeda in Iraq.

00:22:21.500 --> 00:22:24.760
Each card is sort of organized
around some crucial idea

00:22:24.760 --> 00:22:26.220
in the conflict.

00:22:26.220 --> 00:22:29.220
That card stack generated
a tremendous amount

00:22:29.220 --> 00:22:32.340
of inbound linking, which led
to a sharp rise in the Google

00:22:32.340 --> 00:22:33.220
rankings.

00:22:33.220 --> 00:22:35.590
It's been read--
I can't remember

00:22:35.590 --> 00:22:37.590
if this is the page number
or the reader number.

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:40.960
But it's been somethinged more
than 12 million or 15 million

00:22:40.960 --> 00:22:42.800
times at this point.

00:22:42.800 --> 00:22:43.937
So that's a huge success.

00:22:43.937 --> 00:22:45.020
That's one of our biggest.

00:22:45.020 --> 00:22:46.720
And we've had others
that are like that.

00:22:46.720 --> 00:22:48.580
That's our highest
ranked one, but we've

00:22:48.580 --> 00:22:50.430
had others that have
been huge successes.

00:22:50.430 --> 00:22:53.130
Then we've had a number that
have just done nothing at all.

00:22:56.080 --> 00:22:57.840
So one thing we're
trying to figure out

00:22:57.840 --> 00:23:00.339
is how to deal a little bit
with the variability better.

00:23:00.339 --> 00:23:02.130
One thing we're trying
to understand better

00:23:02.130 --> 00:23:05.320
is the beautiful
mysteries of Google.

