00:34:32.030 --> 00:34:34.530
I think that something we've
all discovered in recent years

00:34:34.530 --> 00:34:36.550
is that long form works
really well on the web.

00:34:36.550 --> 00:34:37.949
That people's
attention spans are

00:34:37.949 --> 00:34:39.668
way beyond what we
give them credit for.

00:34:39.668 --> 00:34:41.709
Now, a lot of short stuff
works really well, too,

00:34:41.709 --> 00:34:43.699
and Vox has a
combination of both.

00:34:43.699 --> 00:34:45.780
We do all kinds of stuff.

00:34:45.780 --> 00:34:49.449
But it just is not my experience
that readers punish you

00:34:49.449 --> 00:34:53.320
for going into detail.

00:34:53.320 --> 00:34:56.510
The majority of the stuff
we do that does best

00:34:56.510 --> 00:34:58.610
is actually pretty
detailed, pretty long.

00:34:58.610 --> 00:35:02.240
And the truth is, if you even
think about other organizations

00:35:02.240 --> 00:35:03.610
and outlets, it's often true.

00:35:03.610 --> 00:35:07.610
To use a player who a lot
of people would imagine

00:35:07.610 --> 00:35:10.340
is like the apotheosis of
short on the internet, which

00:35:10.340 --> 00:35:11.140
is BuzzFeed.

00:35:11.140 --> 00:35:12.700
If you really look
at what they do,

00:35:12.700 --> 00:35:17.140
for instance, they are
very intent on signaling

00:35:17.140 --> 00:35:19.430
how long things are going to be.

00:35:19.430 --> 00:35:21.550
They do not have
lists of seven things,

00:35:21.550 --> 00:35:23.820
or three things, or nine things.

00:35:23.820 --> 00:35:28.240
It's 42 things only children
from 1993 will understand.

00:35:28.240 --> 00:35:29.970
It's about showing
that there's going

00:35:29.970 --> 00:35:32.550
to be a level of
comprehensiveness and length

00:35:32.550 --> 00:35:34.140
in here.

00:35:34.140 --> 00:35:37.110
In general, I think the
internet rewards work.

00:35:37.110 --> 00:35:40.577
I think that it rewards stuff
that people find valuable.

00:35:40.577 --> 00:35:42.910
A lot of the short stuff that
works well on the internet

00:35:42.910 --> 00:35:44.550
tends to not actually be short.

00:35:44.550 --> 00:35:48.640
What it tends to be is an
embed of something long.

00:35:48.640 --> 00:35:51.590
So people, I think, will
often say like a John Oliver

00:35:51.590 --> 00:35:54.030
video does really well across
a number of news sites.

00:35:54.030 --> 00:35:55.200
That's short.

00:35:55.200 --> 00:35:58.160
But actually, it's a 17-minute
video about state legislatures

00:35:58.160 --> 00:35:59.160
and why they're corrupt.

00:35:59.160 --> 00:36:01.570
So to the reader it's very long.

00:36:01.570 --> 00:36:04.610
So to some degree I
think we underestimate

00:36:04.610 --> 00:36:07.140
the internet audience
a lot on this stuff.

00:36:07.140 --> 00:36:10.390
I think there is a really
significant audience

00:36:10.390 --> 00:36:12.720
of people who want good content.

00:36:12.720 --> 00:36:15.780
The big polarization, I think,
in terms of online news is

00:36:15.780 --> 00:36:18.557
between people who want
it and people who don't.

00:36:18.557 --> 00:36:20.140
But once you're
bought in, once you're

00:36:20.140 --> 00:36:22.764
one of the people who've decided
as a hobby in your life you're

00:36:22.764 --> 00:36:27.702
going to read the news, you tend
to be into a lot of good stuff.

00:36:27.702 --> 00:36:29.160
RICHARD GINGRAS:
I think the term--

00:36:29.160 --> 00:36:31.640
I'm going to go to
the crowd in the cloud

00:36:31.640 --> 00:36:33.097
again for a second here.

00:36:33.097 --> 00:36:34.180
I think the term utility--

00:36:34.180 --> 00:36:35.070
EZRA KLEIN: It's
weird interacting

00:36:35.070 --> 00:36:36.450
with all these real
people at Google.

00:36:36.450 --> 00:36:37.450
RICHARD GINGRAS: I know.

00:36:37.450 --> 00:36:38.072
It's true.

00:36:38.072 --> 00:36:39.280
They're actually projections.

00:36:42.050 --> 00:36:44.620
I think the word
utility's a good one.

00:36:44.620 --> 00:36:47.160
A phrase that I've often
used is knowledge utility.

00:36:47.160 --> 00:36:49.760
And we had a panel
here recently,

00:36:49.760 --> 00:36:52.010
part of the same series,
with investigative journalist

00:36:52.010 --> 00:36:54.950
from ProPublica Center of
Investigative Journalism.

00:36:54.950 --> 00:36:57.410
ProPublica has been
creating knowledge utilities

00:36:57.410 --> 00:36:59.220
off of data.

00:36:59.220 --> 00:37:01.474
How can I find a
dialysis treatment center

00:37:01.474 --> 00:37:03.390
and understand whether
they're better or worse

00:37:03.390 --> 00:37:04.860
than the one two miles away.

00:37:04.860 --> 00:37:05.360
EZRA KLEIN: They do
incredible jobs with that.

00:37:05.360 --> 00:37:06.526
RICHARD GINGRAS: Great work.

00:37:06.526 --> 00:37:07.610
EZRA KLEIN: Great work.

00:37:07.610 --> 00:37:09.359
RICHARD GINGRAS: Their
newsrooms right now

00:37:09.359 --> 00:37:13.680
are in the area of
20% data journalists.

00:37:13.680 --> 00:37:17.340
So I'm curious at Vox, what's
your view on data journalism?

00:37:17.340 --> 00:37:19.570
How much of it is a part
of what you're doing?

00:37:19.570 --> 00:37:20.970
What you want to do?

00:37:20.970 --> 00:37:23.011
EZRA KLEIN: We have some
exciting data journalist

00:37:23.011 --> 00:37:24.050
announcements coming.

00:37:24.050 --> 00:37:27.070
OK, I have complicated
ideas on this.

00:37:27.070 --> 00:37:29.224
So enjoy your long answer.

00:37:29.224 --> 00:37:31.640
Also, was that a cloud question
or was that your question?

00:37:31.640 --> 00:37:33.660
RICHARD GINGRAS: That
was a cloud question.

00:37:33.660 --> 00:37:35.470
EZRA KLEIN: OK.

00:37:35.470 --> 00:37:38.910
You spoke it so eloquently.

00:37:38.910 --> 00:37:40.030
OK, data journalism.

00:37:40.030 --> 00:37:43.860
We have often been grouped
as a data journalist outlet

00:37:43.860 --> 00:37:47.160
with a bunch of others like
FiveThirtyEight and The Upshot,

00:37:47.160 --> 00:37:49.320
and other things like
that that started roughly

00:37:49.320 --> 00:37:50.590
around the time we did.

00:37:50.590 --> 00:37:53.800
I have not thought of us
as a data journalism shop

00:37:53.800 --> 00:37:56.970
just because we have not really
built out that capacity yet.

00:37:56.970 --> 00:38:00.010
Now, our journals have
to be data literate.

00:38:00.010 --> 00:38:04.640
We have a very high
premium on knowing

00:38:04.640 --> 00:38:07.090
how to do the basic work of
working with spreadsheets,

00:38:07.090 --> 00:38:09.910
of working with graphs,
charts, tables, maps.

00:38:09.910 --> 00:38:12.140
We have a lot of people
who can do regressions.

00:38:12.140 --> 00:38:16.620
It's not like some mysterious
other language in the newsroom.

00:38:16.620 --> 00:38:20.680
So I've tried very hard
to integrate those skills.

00:38:20.680 --> 00:38:22.786
But we've not built too
big of a separate team,

00:38:22.786 --> 00:38:24.910
although we're going to be
making some hires pretty

00:38:24.910 --> 00:38:27.160
shortly in that area, or
announcing some hires pretty

00:38:27.160 --> 00:38:28.034
shortly in that area.

00:38:28.034 --> 00:38:30.409
But let me talk for minute
just about what I think it is,

00:38:30.409 --> 00:38:32.159
because this is where
we're going with it,

00:38:32.159 --> 00:38:34.660
and it's one reason it's taken
us some time to get there.

00:38:34.660 --> 00:38:39.760
I think that data journalism
has frequently been conflated,

00:38:39.760 --> 00:38:43.760
not by ProPublica, but by the
sort of media conversation

00:38:43.760 --> 00:38:46.860
with the data visualization.

00:38:46.860 --> 00:38:48.890
You put up a graph and
people are like ah-ha!

00:38:48.890 --> 00:38:49.910
Data journalism.

00:38:49.910 --> 00:38:50.800
No.

00:38:50.800 --> 00:38:52.720
That's a graph.

00:38:52.720 --> 00:38:54.110
It's a chart.

00:38:54.110 --> 00:38:56.006
That's why I put in
one chart as opposed

00:38:56.006 --> 00:38:58.130
to in one piece of data
journalism in the headline.

00:39:01.390 --> 00:39:04.340
There is a lot of performance
of data on the internet

00:39:04.340 --> 00:39:08.011
right now, much of which I have
been a big part in pushing.

00:39:08.011 --> 00:39:08.510
It's great.

00:39:08.510 --> 00:39:10.200
I hope you all share
it on Facebook.

00:39:10.200 --> 00:39:12.779
But that is not data journalism.

00:39:12.779 --> 00:39:14.820
To me, what is interesting
about data journalism,

00:39:14.820 --> 00:39:18.470
to me, what makes data
journalism journalism is what

00:39:18.470 --> 00:39:25.340
you are doing is you
are figuring out ways

00:39:25.340 --> 00:39:30.180
to create data information
sources that you are then

00:39:30.180 --> 00:39:33.930
using to find and
report stories.

00:39:33.930 --> 00:39:39.120
So to talk about Nate Silver
for a minute, what was amazing

00:39:39.120 --> 00:39:42.470
about Nate's work on
the election is that--

00:39:42.470 --> 00:39:44.510
and I think it was
often misunderstood,

00:39:44.510 --> 00:39:48.740
because people get
very, oh, my god, math.

00:39:48.740 --> 00:39:54.360
Nate had created a model that
was feeding a spreadsheet.

00:39:54.360 --> 00:39:56.970
And every day that
spreadsheet was giving Nate

00:39:56.970 --> 00:39:59.200
a story about the election.

00:39:59.200 --> 00:40:02.801
Nate was the chief correspondent
of Nate Silver spreadsheet.

00:40:02.801 --> 00:40:04.550
That was an amazing
thing to be because he

00:40:04.550 --> 00:40:06.216
had a monopoly
over those stories.

00:40:06.216 --> 00:40:08.590
And the stories are better
than most of the other stories

00:40:08.590 --> 00:40:10.320
people were writing.

00:40:10.320 --> 00:40:12.450
So to me, that was
data journalism.

00:40:12.450 --> 00:40:17.220
Nate had found a way
to pull data sources

00:40:17.220 --> 00:40:21.840
into a comprehensible usable
format that could then

00:40:21.840 --> 00:40:25.970
inform a stream of
ongoing stories.

00:40:25.970 --> 00:40:30.990
Data journalism to me is
doing journalism off of data.

00:40:30.990 --> 00:40:33.140
And so when I think about
how we're going to do it,

00:40:33.140 --> 00:40:35.410
and when I think about
how it needs to be done,

00:40:35.410 --> 00:40:38.530
I think that there's been
too much and too much

00:40:38.530 --> 00:40:41.780
talking about pretty
interactives and graphics,

00:40:41.780 --> 00:40:44.410
and too little about the actual
data side of journalism, which

00:40:44.410 --> 00:40:45.970
is what information sources
are you going to use.

00:40:45.970 --> 00:40:47.970
How are you going to make
them into something that's

00:40:47.970 --> 00:40:49.720
telling you true
facts about the world,

00:40:49.720 --> 00:40:52.050
or at least leading
you towards ways

00:40:52.050 --> 00:40:53.800
of finding true facts
about the world.

00:40:53.800 --> 00:40:55.320
And how you make
that information

00:40:55.320 --> 00:40:57.430
accessible to your
journals, and then how will

00:40:57.430 --> 00:41:00.410
you make it accessible and
transparent to your readers.

00:41:00.410 --> 00:41:02.240
So we're going to be
pushing into that.

00:41:02.240 --> 00:41:04.320
I think we have some
cool ideas there.

00:41:04.320 --> 00:41:06.030
But I think that
for me, we've had

00:41:06.030 --> 00:41:07.680
a lot of data
visualization at Vox.

00:41:07.680 --> 00:41:09.380
We're reasonably good at that.

00:41:09.380 --> 00:41:11.800
But data journalism is
a much harder thing--

00:41:11.800 --> 00:41:13.970
ProPublica is really
one of leaders in it.

00:41:13.970 --> 00:41:15.030
And it is--

00:41:15.030 --> 00:41:17.860
RICHARD GINGRAS:
Making money from it.

00:41:17.860 --> 00:41:18.680
EZRA KLEIN: Yes.

00:41:18.680 --> 00:41:19.680
I can't speak to their--

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:20.763
RICHARD GINGRAS: They are.

00:41:20.763 --> 00:41:22.010
EZRA KLEIN: So that's great.

00:41:22.010 --> 00:41:25.324
I'm a big fan of journalism
that makes money.

00:41:25.324 --> 00:41:26.740
So if it turns out
data journalism

00:41:26.740 --> 00:41:29.010
is money journalism,
that's even better.

00:41:29.010 --> 00:41:33.620
That's my favorite kind
of journalism data.

00:41:33.620 --> 00:41:37.760
So to me, I don't think Vox
has pushed far on that yet.

00:41:37.760 --> 00:41:39.590
We've done a lot of
data visualization,

00:41:39.590 --> 00:41:42.390
but we are building
out the capacity

00:41:42.390 --> 00:41:44.620
and building out a
number of things required

00:41:44.620 --> 00:41:47.490
for us to do the sort
of separate thing

00:41:47.490 --> 00:41:49.010
that I think of as
data journalism,

00:41:49.010 --> 00:41:52.557
not just my reporter knows
how to use a spreadsheet.

00:41:52.557 --> 00:41:54.390
RICHARD GINGRAS: I want
to shift, if we can,

00:41:54.390 --> 00:41:58.720
to another dimension of
the architecture of news.

00:41:58.720 --> 00:42:04.340
And this deals, to me, with
the facet of credibility.

00:42:04.340 --> 00:42:07.670
I mean the internet is
an extraordinary thing.

00:42:07.670 --> 00:42:11.847
It's broadened
expression tremendously.

00:42:11.847 --> 00:42:13.930
Of course, there's more
wheat, there's more chaff.

00:42:13.930 --> 00:42:15.990
It's a maelstrom of expression.

00:42:15.990 --> 00:42:18.880
And anyone with a
thought can do so.

00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:21.780
And as we know, it's also
great at amplifying untruths,

00:42:21.780 --> 00:42:23.010
as well as it is truths.

00:42:25.990 --> 00:42:30.570
Unfortunately, in this era, it
becomes increasingly hard right

00:42:30.570 --> 00:42:34.890
now to differentiate between
the good and the bad.

00:42:34.890 --> 00:42:37.120
We've started a project--
we-- Sally Lehrman

00:42:37.120 --> 00:42:39.570
is here who's also an
esteemed journalist

00:42:39.570 --> 00:42:43.260
and a Fellow at the
Markkula Center for Ethics.

00:42:43.260 --> 00:42:46.720
And we've started an initiative
within the industry called

00:42:46.720 --> 00:42:51.340
The Trust Project, which really
pokes at the notion of how

00:42:51.340 --> 00:42:56.840
can we, in the industry,
evolve the model of journalism

00:42:56.840 --> 00:42:59.860
such that more
dimensions that support

00:42:59.860 --> 00:43:02.390
the credibility of
the work are there.

00:43:02.390 --> 00:43:04.360
And the interesting thing
is that quality news

00:43:04.360 --> 00:43:07.160
organizations, and
I put yours in that,

00:43:07.160 --> 00:43:10.890
are doing the necessary
things to support this.

00:43:10.890 --> 00:43:13.220
You have expertise.

00:43:13.220 --> 00:43:18.090
You do deep work that
supports your conclusions.

00:43:18.090 --> 00:43:21.200
You have editorial
workflows where

00:43:21.200 --> 00:43:24.240
people double check your
work and sign off on it.

00:43:24.240 --> 00:43:29.070
Yet most of this is not
exposed to the audience at all.

00:43:29.070 --> 00:43:32.720
I don't know that Adam Ellick's
story at "The New York Times"

00:43:32.720 --> 00:43:35.140
went through three weeks
of vetting with editors

00:43:35.140 --> 00:43:38.490
and lawyers before he put it
up on the web where it was then

00:43:38.490 --> 00:43:42.240
rewritten 500 times by others
who did not have expertise

00:43:42.240 --> 00:43:44.140
and didn't do his work.

00:43:44.140 --> 00:43:46.300
So I'd really love
to get your thoughts

00:43:46.300 --> 00:43:50.700
as you think about Vox's
evolution of its models

00:43:50.700 --> 00:43:55.160
as to what you think you
might do to really buttress

00:43:55.160 --> 00:43:58.010
the notion that you do
have that credibility

00:43:58.010 --> 00:44:00.510
and expertise to get
me to be comfortable

00:44:00.510 --> 00:44:02.800
trusting what you say.

00:44:02.800 --> 00:44:06.800
EZRA KLEIN: So this is
a really hard problem.

00:44:06.800 --> 00:44:08.709
And it is a harder
problem now than it's even

00:44:08.709 --> 00:44:10.750
been at any other time
when I've been doing this,

00:44:10.750 --> 00:44:13.440
because so many people
who come to your site

00:44:13.440 --> 00:44:16.455
are coming through social media.

00:44:16.455 --> 00:44:18.746
You're getting so many people--
or even through search.

00:44:18.746 --> 00:44:20.287
So you're getting
so many people just

00:44:20.287 --> 00:44:22.560
like they have found
the link or the headline

00:44:22.560 --> 00:44:24.351
and they're coming in
and they don't really

00:44:24.351 --> 00:44:26.500
know what they're getting.

00:44:26.500 --> 00:44:30.050
I remember back in the days
of yore when I started a blog,

00:44:30.050 --> 00:44:32.350
and the way you
got traffic was you

00:44:32.350 --> 00:44:35.050
got direct links
from other people.

00:44:35.050 --> 00:44:36.830
And so you were
getting traffic based

00:44:36.830 --> 00:44:39.910
on an implicit endorsement, or
at times, an anti-endorsement--

00:44:39.910 --> 00:44:41.660
this guy's the stupidest
idiot on the face

00:44:41.660 --> 00:44:44.860
of the earth--
from someone else.

00:44:44.860 --> 00:44:47.415
And so the readership came
with some understanding

00:44:47.415 --> 00:44:48.290
of what was going on.

00:44:51.540 --> 00:44:55.020
If you guys have not read
Richard and his colleagues'

00:44:55.020 --> 00:44:57.042
work on the idea of The
Trust Project on Medium,

00:44:57.042 --> 00:44:57.750
it's worth doing.

00:44:57.750 --> 00:44:58.840
It's very thought provoking.

00:44:58.840 --> 00:45:01.173
And I know that's sort of
what we're talking about here.

00:45:01.173 --> 00:45:04.060
So I've been thinking
about that a lot today,

00:45:04.060 --> 00:45:06.310
and since you sent it to me.

00:45:06.310 --> 00:45:08.930
And let me tell you what
worries me about all this stuff,

00:45:08.930 --> 00:45:11.096
because I really do want
to find an answer to this

00:45:11.096 --> 00:45:11.970
and I don't know how.

00:45:15.540 --> 00:45:19.450
So we invest a lot
at Vox on things

00:45:19.450 --> 00:45:21.970
that I think do increase
the quality of the product.

00:45:21.970 --> 00:45:23.130
We have a lot of editors.

00:45:23.130 --> 00:45:24.280
Everything gets edited.

00:45:24.280 --> 00:45:27.220
Everything now over 800
words gets copy edited.

00:45:27.220 --> 00:45:30.740
It gets a secondary copy
edit before it goes up.

00:45:30.740 --> 00:45:35.490
When we do data visualization,
that has a separate look

00:45:35.490 --> 00:45:37.220
and run through.

00:45:37.220 --> 00:45:40.220
We have a very tight
corrections policy,

00:45:40.220 --> 00:45:44.250
where we will correct-- in
some ways maybe too tight.

00:45:44.250 --> 00:45:47.060
But we really try to be, like
if we get anything wrong.

00:45:47.060 --> 00:45:50.640
Like I wrote 2005 rather than
'06-- that's a correction.

00:45:50.640 --> 00:45:54.480
We put up a chart from the
US Department of Agriculture.

00:45:54.480 --> 00:45:55.990
Their chart was wrong.

00:45:55.990 --> 00:45:58.080
We got them to
correct their chart.

00:45:58.080 --> 00:45:59.260
We corrected our story.

00:46:01.880 --> 00:46:04.440
We're doing a lot that is
meant to really build up

00:46:04.440 --> 00:46:08.090
transparency and credibility
with the audience.

00:46:08.090 --> 00:46:12.200
Here's where I get
scared of what we know

00:46:12.200 --> 00:46:15.190
and what we don't know about
how we'll end up interacting.

00:46:15.190 --> 00:46:15.700
Two things.

00:46:15.700 --> 00:46:18.930
One is formalism,
trust formalism.

00:46:18.930 --> 00:46:20.482
So I think of
"Bloomberg News" here,

00:46:20.482 --> 00:46:21.940
which I've done a
lot of work with.

00:46:21.940 --> 00:46:23.682
I was a columnist
for "Bloomberg View."

00:46:23.682 --> 00:46:24.390
Everything there.

00:46:24.390 --> 00:46:25.910
You have the name
of the editor, you

00:46:25.910 --> 00:46:26.960
have the name of
the copy editor.

00:46:26.960 --> 00:46:29.400
Medium actually does a nice
job of this on their long form

00:46:29.400 --> 00:46:31.466
stories-- who was the
illustrator, who was the--

00:46:31.466 --> 00:46:32.841
and it's really
showing you there

00:46:32.841 --> 00:46:34.920
were a lot of people who
worked on this piece.

00:46:34.920 --> 00:46:36.410
On features we
actually do it too.

00:46:36.410 --> 00:46:38.446
We show on features
who is the editor, who

00:46:38.446 --> 00:46:40.070
is the designer, who
is the writer, who

00:46:40.070 --> 00:46:42.320
is the-- all the
different players that

00:46:42.320 --> 00:46:45.750
were involved to make the piece.

00:46:45.750 --> 00:46:47.190
The only thing I
would say is that

00:46:47.190 --> 00:46:51.250
in my experience of the internet
and of journalism in general,

00:46:51.250 --> 00:46:54.040
that is actually
not what separates

00:46:54.040 --> 00:46:55.436
good work and bad work.

00:46:55.436 --> 00:46:56.810
It is not what
separates things I

00:46:56.810 --> 00:46:59.470
think you should trust from
things I think you should not.

00:46:59.470 --> 00:47:01.240
Editing is an incredibly
important thing.

00:47:01.240 --> 00:47:02.680
It makes work so much better.

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:03.952
It really is critical.

00:47:03.952 --> 00:47:05.410
And we are hiring
a lot of editors.

00:47:05.410 --> 00:47:07.930
If any of you would like to
be our deputy culture editor,

00:47:07.930 --> 00:47:10.060
let me know.

00:47:10.060 --> 00:47:16.430
But a lot of the true lies
on the internet are edited.

00:47:16.430 --> 00:47:18.750
And a lot of them
aren't even factually

00:47:18.750 --> 00:47:21.850
wrong, they're just
completely incorrect.

00:47:21.850 --> 00:47:29.920
And I think there are a lot of
ways to-- if we all just start

00:47:29.920 --> 00:47:31.930
writing down our editors
and our copy editors

00:47:31.930 --> 00:47:36.930
and creating a sort of map
of how much we did on it,

00:47:36.930 --> 00:47:40.890
I worry that's going to get
gamed, because that's a model.

00:47:40.890 --> 00:47:42.050
It's like a clear thing.

00:47:42.050 --> 00:47:45.179
It's a clear-- and stuff
like that, it begins to work.

00:47:45.179 --> 00:47:46.970
If Google began to put
it in the algorithm,

00:47:46.970 --> 00:47:48.830
it will get gamed rapidly.

00:47:48.830 --> 00:47:50.830
I've just seen this before.

00:47:50.830 --> 00:47:51.850
So that worries me.

00:47:51.850 --> 00:47:53.391
And then the other
thing that worries

00:47:53.391 --> 00:47:59.570
me is somehow making
trust too much of a stand

00:47:59.570 --> 00:48:01.540
in for resources.

00:48:01.540 --> 00:48:03.550
A lot of the really
important thinking

00:48:03.550 --> 00:48:06.100
and a lot of the really
true things on the internet

00:48:06.100 --> 00:48:09.560
come from people outside
of the mainstream

00:48:09.560 --> 00:48:13.920
for all kinds of, in some ways
obvious, reasons, I think.

00:48:13.920 --> 00:48:16.230
I think back to
the Iraq War, when

00:48:16.230 --> 00:48:19.770
Juan Cole, who is a Middle
Eastern history professor-- I

00:48:19.770 --> 00:48:21.770
believe he was out at U
Michigan at that point--

00:48:21.770 --> 00:48:23.340
was one of the
really best guides.

00:48:23.340 --> 00:48:24.810
Not literally everything
he said was right,

00:48:24.810 --> 00:48:27.460
but compared to what you were
getting out of the main papers,

00:48:27.460 --> 00:48:29.730
this blogger, who was
just a history professor,

00:48:29.730 --> 00:48:34.927
was way better, and he was
a way truer guide to it.

00:48:34.927 --> 00:48:37.260
But he would have been destroyed
by something like this,

00:48:37.260 --> 00:48:39.450
because he had no editors,
he had no copy editors.

00:48:39.450 --> 00:48:40.700
He just had his own expertise.

00:48:43.600 --> 00:48:45.730
So when I think about this,
I think of two things,

00:48:45.730 --> 00:48:47.100
and they're fuzzy
and I don't like it,

00:48:47.100 --> 00:48:49.250
because I want people to
know the work we're putting

00:48:49.250 --> 00:48:50.625
into what we're
doing, and I just

00:48:50.625 --> 00:48:53.540
have not figured
out a good solution.

00:48:53.540 --> 00:48:56.720
But one, I do think of the
card stacks as being part of it

00:48:56.720 --> 00:49:00.150
for us, because I think that
if you can show that you've

00:49:00.150 --> 00:49:02.210
been really working
on this story a lot,

00:49:02.210 --> 00:49:05.390
you've been diving deep into
it, you've been doing the job,

00:49:05.390 --> 00:49:07.340
then at least you
can show your reader

00:49:07.340 --> 00:49:09.020
why they should trust you.

00:49:09.020 --> 00:49:11.800
You can show them you didn't
just come to this today

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:14.570
because you noticed
on CrowdTangle it

00:49:14.570 --> 00:49:16.110
was popping on Facebook.

00:49:16.110 --> 00:49:18.950
You've been covering, say, the
Bill Cosby sexual harassment

00:49:18.950 --> 00:49:20.710
things for six months now.

00:49:20.710 --> 00:49:22.430
You've written 200 stories.

00:49:22.430 --> 00:49:23.640
You've done a full timeline.

00:49:23.640 --> 00:49:26.270
You really know what's going on.

00:49:26.270 --> 00:49:30.400
Another thing there, which
this one isn't as helpful,

00:49:30.400 --> 00:49:32.500
but is really just--
and it's an old blogging

00:49:32.500 --> 00:49:35.310
thing is showing your work,
is linking to your work.

00:49:35.310 --> 00:49:37.560
I'll tell you a place where
I really worry about this.

00:49:37.560 --> 00:49:41.470
We talked about the performance
of data a few minutes ago.

00:49:41.470 --> 00:49:44.680
There is a bad habit journalists
have, and we've done it too--

00:49:44.680 --> 00:49:47.780
I'm not exempting
us-- to treat whatever

00:49:47.780 --> 00:49:50.590
is in an abstract
of a working paper

00:49:50.590 --> 00:49:52.660
as a true fact about the world.

00:49:52.660 --> 00:49:56.680
We use academic papers,
we use academic research

00:49:56.680 --> 00:50:00.886
as some kind of synonym
for this is correct.

00:50:00.886 --> 00:50:02.260
These people are
at a university,

00:50:02.260 --> 00:50:06.500
so this is a true estimate
of the macroeconomic impact

00:50:06.500 --> 00:50:08.410
of blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:50:08.410 --> 00:50:11.947
Whereas, that's very rarely--
it's very rarely that simple.

00:50:11.947 --> 00:50:13.780
So something that we're
thinking about a lot

00:50:13.780 --> 00:50:18.610
on this particular piece
of it is how not just

00:50:18.610 --> 00:50:23.030
to show the readers we're
being not just data informed,

00:50:23.030 --> 00:50:24.590
but data skeptical.

00:50:24.590 --> 00:50:26.370
But actually make
sure we have processes

00:50:26.370 --> 00:50:32.774
that force our writers to know
what the actual data says too.

00:50:32.774 --> 00:50:34.940
And I've thought a lot about
it, and we may actually

00:50:34.940 --> 00:50:38.300
do something like this of
having annotations in which it's

00:50:38.300 --> 00:50:41.260
boring to explain the
methodology of things

00:50:41.260 --> 00:50:43.920
in a piece because you might
have to do it six times

00:50:43.920 --> 00:50:45.420
and it's not that interesting.

00:50:45.420 --> 00:50:47.182
But if you have a
strong annotation system

00:50:47.182 --> 00:50:48.390
maybe you do want to do that.

00:50:48.390 --> 00:50:50.380
Maybe particularly when you're
relying heavily on a study,

00:50:50.380 --> 00:50:53.010
you do want to be saying here
is how the study was done.

00:50:53.010 --> 00:50:54.650
Here's what the sample size was.

00:50:54.650 --> 00:50:56.900
You don't need to roll over
that if you don't want it,

00:50:56.900 --> 00:50:57.975
but it's there if you want it.

00:50:57.975 --> 00:50:59.750
And then at least you
know and the reader

00:50:59.750 --> 00:51:02.990
knows that the writer at least
knows how the study was done.

00:51:02.990 --> 00:51:05.100
So I'm trying to think
about things like that

00:51:05.100 --> 00:51:10.010
where we can somehow show not
that we had the resources to do

00:51:10.010 --> 00:51:12.260
the work, or not even
what our process was,

00:51:12.260 --> 00:51:15.550
but in a very specific way
on this particular article.

00:51:15.550 --> 00:51:18.910
Like we went deeper even
than what you see here.

00:51:18.910 --> 00:51:22.420
We made sure we understood
the underpinnings of it.

00:51:22.420 --> 00:51:24.369
But I'll just be
flatly honest with you

00:51:24.369 --> 00:51:25.910
because I don't want
to bullshit you.

00:51:25.910 --> 00:51:27.368
I have not come to
anything on this

00:51:27.368 --> 00:51:29.740
that I feel super good about.

00:51:29.740 --> 00:51:31.700
I do not know how to
say to someone, how

00:51:31.700 --> 00:51:32.730
to show someone clearly.

00:51:36.630 --> 00:51:38.546
We have, for years
before this, been

00:51:38.546 --> 00:51:40.420
talking to the relevant
experts in this space

00:51:40.420 --> 00:51:43.110
and have come to the story
with a body of knowledge.

00:51:43.110 --> 00:51:45.620
And when we tell
you what's going on,

00:51:45.620 --> 00:51:48.090
even though our take maybe
was less interesting than some

00:51:48.090 --> 00:51:50.080
of the hot takes by people who
have not been following this

00:51:50.080 --> 00:51:52.080
in any clear way and
parachuted in today,

00:51:52.080 --> 00:51:54.080
it's a more trustworthy one.

00:51:54.080 --> 00:51:56.040
I've not figured
out how to do that.

00:51:56.040 --> 00:51:58.040
I'm hoping you will
figure it out for me.

00:51:58.040 --> 00:51:58.940
RICHARD GINGRAS: It's
a complex problem,

00:51:58.940 --> 00:52:01.530
and I wouldn't pretend that
there are silver bullets,

00:52:01.530 --> 00:52:03.800
and there's a lot
more to discuss there.

00:52:03.800 --> 00:52:05.400
We're almost out of
time, but maybe we

00:52:05.400 --> 00:52:08.734
have time for one more fast
question and a fast answer.

00:52:08.734 --> 00:52:09.400
Anyone want to--

00:52:09.400 --> 00:52:09.680
EZRA KLEIN: I make no promises.

00:52:09.680 --> 00:52:11.310
RICHARD GINGRAS:
--volunteer with one?

00:52:11.310 --> 00:52:12.393
Who's got a fast question?

00:52:15.390 --> 00:52:17.830
AUDIENCE: Do you have
any advice for Google?

00:52:17.830 --> 00:52:22.360
What could we do to help users
benefit from good journalism

00:52:22.360 --> 00:52:23.450
that we aren't doing?

00:52:23.450 --> 00:52:25.830
EZRA KLEIN: Aside from lifting
Vox in the search rank,

00:52:25.830 --> 00:52:27.955
and this is just a matter
of algorithmic precision.

00:52:30.954 --> 00:52:32.870
I'll go back to persistence
here for a minute.

00:52:32.870 --> 00:52:35.379
I think the thing that Google
should be thinking about,

00:52:35.379 --> 00:52:36.920
Google News should
be thinking about,

00:52:36.920 --> 00:52:38.794
maybe that Facebook
should be thinking about,

00:52:38.794 --> 00:52:41.330
that others should be thinking
about is to what degree

00:52:41.330 --> 00:52:44.300
the algorithms that
y'all use right now,

00:52:44.300 --> 00:52:50.310
end up prizing iterative, brand
new reporting all the time.

00:52:50.310 --> 00:52:55.500
To what degree recency is
a measure that is actually

00:52:55.500 --> 00:52:58.920
forcing us to do things in
a way that is not the best

00:52:58.920 --> 00:53:01.080
way for our readers,
or that we're

00:53:01.080 --> 00:53:04.199
capable of in
digital journalism.

00:53:04.199 --> 00:53:06.490
I'll use Facebook as the
example here because honestly,

00:53:06.490 --> 00:53:08.698
I know a little bit less
about how your search works.

00:53:08.698 --> 00:53:12.570
But you actually get downgraded
for putting the same URL

00:53:12.570 --> 00:53:15.420
into Facebook repeatedly.

00:53:15.420 --> 00:53:19.290
But if I want to do an explainer
on, say, something fast moving,

00:53:19.290 --> 00:53:20.960
instead of rewriting
it all the time,

00:53:20.960 --> 00:53:23.610
I want to keep updating that
and making that the very best it

00:53:23.610 --> 00:53:24.110
can be.

00:53:24.110 --> 00:53:26.484
And I can make that piece
into something much richer

00:53:26.484 --> 00:53:28.650
than I could if I were
having to constantly split it

00:53:28.650 --> 00:53:29.810
into new pieces.

00:53:29.810 --> 00:53:32.257
But I'm going to get
penalized for doing that.

00:53:32.257 --> 00:53:34.340
And so I think that something
that you guys should

00:53:34.340 --> 00:53:39.110
be thinking about is how
much-- moving journalism

00:53:39.110 --> 00:53:42.060
onto the internet does not
make it digital journalism.

00:53:42.060 --> 00:53:43.910
Just the fact that it's
hosted on a web page

00:53:43.910 --> 00:53:45.120
does not get you there.

00:53:45.120 --> 00:53:49.450
And so a lot of us have built
our workflows, our processes,

00:53:49.450 --> 00:53:52.100
all kinds of things, in
journalism and outside of it,

00:53:52.100 --> 00:53:56.810
based upon what we intuitively
understand as journalism,

00:53:56.810 --> 00:53:59.160
what our habits
are in journalism.

00:53:59.160 --> 00:54:02.400
And there's a lot more pressure
keeping us in old workflows

00:54:02.400 --> 00:54:03.240
than people realize.

00:54:03.240 --> 00:54:05.050
The way the publishing
tools are made.

00:54:05.050 --> 00:54:07.170
The way the social
algorithms work.

00:54:07.170 --> 00:54:09.030
All kinds of things
push us to do things

00:54:09.030 --> 00:54:10.730
kind of like they've
always been done,

00:54:10.730 --> 00:54:12.440
just published on the internet.

00:54:12.440 --> 00:54:14.550
So if I were you
guys, I'd be thinking

00:54:14.550 --> 00:54:17.702
long-term about how to
make sure that-- I'm not

00:54:17.702 --> 00:54:20.160
saying you should push away
from how things have been done,

00:54:20.160 --> 00:54:24.460
but how to make sure that
you are not penalizing

00:54:24.460 --> 00:54:27.190
non-traditional approaches
to telling these stories

00:54:27.190 --> 00:54:28.524
and delivering this information.

00:54:28.524 --> 00:54:29.898
RICHARD GINGRAS:
Very good point,

00:54:29.898 --> 00:54:32.450
and I think everyone here
would agree with that.

00:54:32.450 --> 00:54:35.190
I want to thank you very much,
Ezra, for being here with us.

00:54:35.190 --> 00:54:43.030
[APPLAUSE]

00:54:43.030 --> 00:54:45.230
RICHARD GINGRAS: For
your thoughtfulness,

00:54:45.230 --> 00:54:47.800
and most importantly, for
your efforts to continue

00:54:47.800 --> 00:54:50.300
to move the ball forward, and
rethinking the future of news.

00:54:50.300 --> 00:54:52.258
EZRA KLEIN: Well, thank
you all for coming out.

00:54:52.258 --> 00:54:53.960
RICHARD GINGRAS: Thank you.

